Scientific Name:
Triticum spp.: 
Triticum aestivum 
Triticum durum 
Triticum spelta
Definition: Common and durum wheat are the main types. Among common wheat, the main varieties are spring and winter, hard and soft, and red and white. At the national level, different varieties should be reported separately, reflecting their different uses. It includes meslin (a mixture wheat/rye). Used mainly for human food.

Defined broadly to include meal, groats and pellets. Strong flours from hard wheat are used for bread, while durum wheat flour is used primarily for pasta. Weaker flours from soft wheat are mainly used in cakes, pastries, biscuits and certain noodles.
Defined broadly to include sharps and other residue from the milling, sifting or other working of the grain. Contains a little flour.

Pasta made from semolina, or flour, that is mixed with water and kneaded into a dough. Other ingredients may be included as well. The dough is then shaped into various forms. This heading is limited to macaroni that is not cooked, stuffed or otherwise prepared.

The seed embryo. Whole or rolled germ is used for oil extraction by solvents. Flaked or ground germ is used in bakers' wares, dietetic preparations, feed supplements and in pharmaceutical preparations.
A baked product of flour or meal of cereals, especially wheat. Includes ordinary, unleavened, crackers, rusks, etc.
Whole wheat grains that are boiled, dried and cracked, either between stones or in a hand mill. Very popular in the Near East
All baked products excluding those listed under bread. Pastry products may contain ingredients other than wheat flour, such as milk, eggs, sugar, honey, starch, fats, fruit, seeds, etc.

Starch is the carbohydrate component in many plant cells. A white, odourless powder that is insoluble in cold water, it forms a paste in hot water. Wheat starch is used for human consumption and animal feed, and is processed into glucose and dextrine for industrial use. It is usually obtained from low-quality flour.
A by-product of the industrial production of starch, wheat gluten is the preferred cereal gluten for food purposes. Uses include enriching protein in flours for bread, pasta, etc.
Low-alcohol beverages from fermented flour, e.g. Korean jakju and takju.
Rice grain after threshing and winnowing.Also known as rice in the husk and rough rice. Used mainly for human food.
Rice grain without hulls or husks. Also known as brown or cargo rice.
White rice milled from imported husked rice. Includes semi-milled, whole-milled and parboiled rice.
White rice milled from locally grown paddy. Includes semi-milled, whole-milled and parboiled rice.
Residues from the selection of whole-grain, milled rice.
A by-product of the industrial production of starch. Not suitable for food use.
See 0023 Rice starch is usually obtained from broken rice. Use primarily in the photographic industry to prepare "matt" paper.
A by-product of polishing brown rice, comprising the pericarp, aleurone layer, embryo and some endosperm.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Extracted from bran by pressure or, more frequently, by solvents.
A residue of the extraction of oil. Also known as de-oiled rice bran.
Produced by milling broken or milled rice. Finely ground rice flour is widely used in infant foods and in noodles. It is not used in bread because it lacks the necessary gluten-forming protein.
Low-alcohol beverages, such as rice wine and sake.
Foods prepared by swelling and roasting cereals or cereal products, e.g. corn flakes, puffed rice; cereals o/t maize, in grain form, precooked or otherwise prepared.

Scientific Name:
Hordeum spp.: 
Hordeum disticum 
Hordeum hexasticum 
Hordeum vulgare
Common Name:
two-row barley 
six-row barley 
four-row barley
Definition: Tolerates poorer soils and lower temperatures better than does wheat. Varieties include with husk and without (naked). Used as a livestock feed, for malt and for preparing foods. The roasted grains are a coffee substitute.
Whole-seed barley with the husks, hulls and bran removed.
Small, round pellets obtained by the further milling of pot barley. This definition also includes kibbled, rolled or flaked grains.
A by-product of the production of pot barley.
Fine flour and course meal obtained as milling by-products of pearled barley.

A grain - usually barley - that has been germinated through a soaking process and then dried. Malt is used in brewing and distilling, and as a nutrient additive. Includes whole, ground, flour, and roasted malt, but excludes extracts and preparations.
A concentrated solution from water-macerated malt, which is used in infant and dietetic foods and in bread baking.

Beverage that may be alcoholic or non-alcoholic that is made from fermented malted cereals (mainly barley), water and hops. Non-malted cereals may also be used. The FAO definition differs from the main international classifications in that it includes non-alcoholic beer.

A grain with a high germ content. At the national level, hybrid and ordinary maize should be reported separately owing to widely different yields and uses. Used largely for animal feed and commercial starch production.
The seed embryo that is separated during processing and is valued mainly for its oil.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
A by-product of the milling of shelled maize.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Extracted from germ by pressure or by solvents.
A residue of the extraction of oil from germ.
Maize protein is often called gluten, although it lacks the quality characteristics of wheat gluten. It is separated from maize during commercial wet milling and used to enrich animal feeds.
See 0023. The primary product of the large- scale industrial wet-milling process. Used mainly for the production of glucose, dextrin and alcohol.
Prepared either from malted or unmalted cereal.
Although separate data are reported for white maize production owing to its regional importance, its production is also included in 0056.
A variety of maize that is eaten after the kernels have been heated and have "popped".
A grain that is tolerant of poor soils, high latitudes and altitudes. Mainly used in making bread, whisky and beer. When fed to livestock, it is generally mixed with other grains.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets. In northern countries, rye flour is used primarily in bread.
A milling by-product.
A plant with open, spreading panicle-bearing large spikelets. Used primarily in breakfast foods. Makes excellent fodder for horses.
Obtained by crushing or rolling the whole or broken grain; includes grains flaked, hulled or otherwise worked for human consumption.
By-product of milling oats for human consumption, containing mainly hulls and fragments of the endosperm (oat millfeed), as well as residues from hulling, rolling, flaking, etc.

Scientific Name:
Including among all: 
Echinocloa frumentacea 
Eleusine coracana 
Panicum miliaceum 
Paspalum scrobiculatum 
Pennisetum glaucum 
Setaria italica
Common Name:
barnyard or Japanese millet 
ragi, finger or African millet 
common, golden or proso millet 
koda or ditch millet 
pearl or cattail millet 
foxtail millet
Definition: Small-grained cereals that include a large number of different botanical species. Originated by the domestication of wild African grasses in the Nile valley and the Sahel zone, millets were subsequently taken to China and India. These cereals tolerate arid conditions and possess a small, highly nutritious grain that stores well. Used locally, both as a food and as a livestock feed. In all areas where they are cultivated, millets are used in traditional beer brewing. Also used as a feed for birds. It does not include Teff (Eragrostis abyssinica) cf. 0108.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
A milling by-product.
A traditional beer prepared in African countries in which millets are cultivated. It is normally consumed while still fermenting.

Scientific Name:
Sorghum spp.: 
Sorghum guineense 
Sorghum vulgare 
Sorghum dura
Common Name:
guinea corn 
common, milo, feterita, kaffir corn 
durra, jowar, kaoliang
Definition: A cereal that has both food and feed uses. Sorghum is a major food grain in most of Africa, where it is also used in traditional beer brewing. It is desirable to report hybrid and other varieties separately.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
A milling by-product.
A traditional beer prepared in African countries in which sorghum is cultivated. It is normally consumed while still fermenting.
A minor cereal cultivated primarily in northern regions. Buckwheat is considered a cereal, although it does not belong to the gramineous family.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets. The flour is normally used in bread and crackers, and is also mixed with wheat flour. Meal and groats are normally used for soups.
A milling by-product.
A minor cereal, which tolerates high altitudes, quinoa is cultivated primarily in Andean countries. Used for food and to make chicha, a fermented beverage.

Scientific Name:
Digitaria spp.: 
Digitaria exilis 
Digitaria iburua
Common Name:
fonio or findi 
black fonio or hungry rice
Definition: A minor cereal of importance only in West Africa where it is eaten in place of rice during famines. The seeds are cooked by steaming the whole grain.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
A milling by-product.
A minor cereal that is a cross between wheat and rye, combining the quality and yield of wheat with the hardiness of rye.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
A milling by-product.
Minor cereal normally used as bird feed.
A mixture of cereal species that are sown and harvested together. It does not include: meslin (a mixture wheat/rye).
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
A milling by-product.

Scientific Name:
Including among all: 
Chenopodium pallidicaule 
Amaranthus caudatus 
Coix lacryma-jobi 
Zizania aquatica 
Teff
Common Name:
canagua or coaihua 
quihuicha or Inca wheat 
adlay or Job's tears 
wild rice 
Eragrostis abyssinica
Definition: Other cereal crops that are not identified separately because of their minor relevance at the international level. Because of their limited local importance, some countries report cereals under this commodity heading that are classified individually by FAO.
Preparations for infant consumption, usually containing some non-cereal ingredients.
Communion wafers, empty cachets for pharmaceutical use and sealing wafers.
Broadly defined to include meal, groats and pellets.
A milling by-product.
Cereal grains, excluding barley and oats, that are either rolled, flaked, pearled, sliced or kibbled.
Used in the preparation of bakers' wares.

FCL Title: Food Preparations of Flour, Meal or Malt Extract
Definition: Food preparations of flour, meal, starch or malt extracts, that either do not contain, or contain less than 50%, cocoa powder. Also, food preparations of milk that either do not contain, or contain less than 10%, cocoa powder.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: A seasonal crop grown in temperate zones all over the world, but primarily in the northern hemisphere.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Produced from tubers that have been peeled, dried and milled. Includes flour, meal, flakes, granules and pellets.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Peeled potatoes that are either cooked or uncooked, sliced or unsliced, and then frozen.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: A carbohydrate found in many plant cells. A white odourless powder that is insoluble in cold water, but forms a paste in hot water. Has wide food and non-food uses.
The residue and waste from the preparation of potatoes.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: A product obtained by heating potato starch mixed with water. Tapioca may be in the form of flakes, grains, pearls, siftings, seeds or other similar forms. Used in the preparation of soups and puddings or in foods for invalids.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: A seasonal crop grown in tropical and subtropical regions. Used mainly for human food. Trade data cover fresh and dried tubers, whether or not sliced or in the form or pellets.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Scientific Name:
Manihot esculenta; Manihot utilissima
Manihot palmata; Manihot dulcis
Definition: A semi-permanent crop grown in tropical and subtropical regions. Sometimes bitter and sweet cassavas are referred to as separate species, the former being M. esculenta and the latter M. palmata, but this is incorrect since the toxicity varies according to location. Cassava is the staple food in many tropical countries. It is not traded internationally in its fresh state because tubers deteriorate very rapidly.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: A product of tubers that have been peeled, dried and milled; mainly for human consumption. Includes flour, meal and flakes.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: See 0121. Obtained from cassava starch and used in the preparation of puddings and in infant foods.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Includes peeled, sliced and sun-dried (cassava chips), as well as ground and compressed cassava (pellets). Used mainly as livestock feed.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: See 0119. The principal industrial outlet for cassava. Cassava starch is used in the foodstuffs, textile and paper industries for the manufacture of plywood and veneer, adhesives, glucose and dextrine.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Several plants are included in this group, some with edible tubers and others with edible stems (also called aroids). Yautia is grown mainly in the Caribbean and is used for food. Trade data cover both fresh and dried yautia.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Aroids cultivated for their edible starchy corms or underground stems. Taro is grown throughout the tropics for food. Trade data cover both fresh and dried taro.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: The principal edible yams are widely grown throughout the tropics. A starchy staple foodstuff, normally eaten as a vegetable, boiled, baked or fried. In West Africa they are consumed mainly as "fufu", a stiff glutinous dough. Trade data cover both fresh and dried yams.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Scientific Name:
Including among all: 
Arracacoa xanthorrhiza 
Maranta arundinacea 
Cyperus esculentus 
Metroxylon spp. 
Oxalis tuberosa and Ullucus tuberosus 
Pachyrxhizus erosus, Pachyrxhizus angulatus 
Tropaeolum tuberosum 
Helianthus tuberosus
Common Name:
arracacha 
arrowroot 
chufa 
sago palm 
oca and ullucu 
yam bean, jicama 
mashua 
Jerusalem artichoke, topinambur
Definition: Other tubers, roots or rhizomes, fresh, that are not identified separately because of their minor relevance at the international level. Because of their limited local importance, some countries report roots and tubers under this commodity heading that are classified individually by FAO.

FCL Title: Flour of Roots and Tubers nes
Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Flour and meal produced from roots and tubers o/t potatoes and cassava.

Group: 2 - ROOTS AND TUBERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Other tubers, roots or rizhomes, dried, o/t potatoes and cassava.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Or levulose, monosaccharide, present with glucose in sweet fruits and honey.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Produced industrially from starch by hydrolysis with malt diastase. Used in the brewing industry.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: In some producing countries, marginal quantities of sugar cane are consumed, either directly as food or in the form of juice.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: In some producing countries, marginal quantities are consumed, either directly as food or in the preparation of jams.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: A non-refined, crystallized material derived from the juices of sugar-cane stalk and consisting either wholly or essentially of sucrose.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: A non-refined, crystallized material derived from the juices extracted from the root of the sugar beet and consisting either wholly or essentially of sucrose.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Maple syrup is produced by atmospheric boiling of maple sap in an open-pan evaporator. Continuing the evaporation process until the syrup crystalizes yields maple sugar.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Scientific Name:
Including among all: 
Acer saccharum 
Sorghum saccharatum 
Arenga saccharifera
Common Name:
sugar maple 
sweet sorghum 
sugar palm
Definition: Includes minor sugar crops of local importance. In the case of saps, production is to be expressed in liquid equivalent.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: The sum of codes 0158 and 0159. Processed further to obtain refined sugar.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Generally derived from sugar cane through traditional methods without centrifugation.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Production covers domestic production, plus or minus imports and/or exports of raw centrifugal sugar in terms of refined sugar.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: A by-product of the extraction or refining of beet or cane sugar or of the production of fructose from maize. Used for feed, food, industrial alcohol, alcoholic beverages and ethanol.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Monosaccharide found in fruits and honey, commercially produced from glucose, sucrose or by hydrolysis of inulin (polysaccharide found mainly in the tubers of the dahlia and the Jerusalem artichoke). Especially suitable for use by diabetics.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Includes invert sugar, caramel, golden syrup, artificial honey, maltose other than chemically pure, sorghum and palm sugars. See also the general note in the introduction.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Sugar confectionery, including chewing gum, that does not contain cocoa. Includes white chocolate.
Residue from the extraction of sugar from the root of sugar beets. Used for animal feed.
Residue consisting of the fibrous portion of the sugar cane after the juice has been extracted. Used as a fuel in sugar mills, as an animal feed, and in paper production.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Glucose is a monosaccharide produced by hydrolysing starch with acids and/or enzymes. Dextrose is chemically pure glucose. Used in the food industry, in brewing, in tobacco fermentation and in pharmaceutical products.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Also known as milk sugar. Produced commercially from whey.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: High-intensity or low-caloric sweetening agents that are produced chemically.

Group: 3 - SUGAR CROPS AND SWEETENERS AND DERIVED PRODUCTS
Definition: Also known as HFCS (high-fructose corn syrup), HFSS (high-fructose starch syrup), HFGS (high-fructose glucose syrup). Isoglucose is a new type of starch syrup where glucose has been isomerized to fructose by using one or more isomerizing enzymes. Most important of the sweeteners manufactured from maize starch. Widely used in the production of food and soft drinks.

Scientific Name:
Phaseolus and Vigna spp.: 
Phaseolus vulgaris 
Phaseolus lunatus 
Phaseolus angularis or Vigna angularis 
Phaseolus aureus 
Phaseolus mungo or Vigna mungo 
Phaseolus coccineus 
Phaseolus calcaratus 
Phaseolus aconitifolius 
Phaseolus acutifolius 
Vigna radiata 
Vigna aconitifolia
Common Name:
kidney, haricot bean 
lima, butter bean 
adzuki bean 
mungo bean, golden, green gram 
black gram, urd 
scarlet runner bean 
rice bean 
moth bean 
tepary bean
Definition:
Includes species of Phaseolus and Vigna. 
The class does not include: Vigna sinensis (Cow peas) cf. 0195 and Vigna or Voandzeia subterranea (Bambara beans) cf. 0203.

Scientific Name:
Vicia faba: 
Vicia faba var. equina 
Vicia faba var. major 
Vicia faba var. minor
Definition: No definition available.
No definition available.
No definition available
No definition available.

Common Name: pigeon pea, cajan pea, Congo bean
Definition: No definition available.
No definition available.
These beand are grown underground in a similar way to groundnuts
Used mainly for animal feed.
Used primarily for feed, though in some parts of Africa and in Latin America some varieties are cultivated for human food.

Scientific Name:
Including among all: 
Dolichos spp. 
Canavalia spp. 
Psophocarpus tetragonolobus 
Cyamopsis tetragonoloba 
Stizolobium spp. 
Pachyrrhizus erosus
Common Name:
lablab or hyacinth bean 
jack or sword bean 
winged bean 
guar bean 
velvet bean 
yam bean
Definition: Other pulses that are not identified separately because of their minor relevance at the international level. Because of their limited local importance, some countries report pulses under this heading that are classified individually by FAO.
Produced through milling or grinding of pulses. This heading also includes meal.
Bran, sharps and other residues from the milling or working of pulses.
No definition available.
Produced mainly in East Africa, India and Brazil.

Scientific Name:
Castanea spp.: 
Castanea vesca 
Castanea vulgaris 
Castanea sativa
Definition: Produced mainly in Europe and Asia.

Scientific Name:
Prunus amygdalus 
Prunus communis 
Amygdalus communis
Definition: Produced mainly in Mediterranean countries, the United States and Asia.
Produced in temperate zones of the Northern Hemisphere, particularly in the United States.
Produced mainly in the Near East and the United States.

Scientific Name: Cola nitida; Cola vera; Cola acuminata
Definition: Produced mainly in Africa. Kola nuts, containing 2.4 to 2.6% caffeine, are commonly chewed by the local population. Much used in Europe and America in the production of beverages.
Produced mainly in Mediterranean countries and the United States.
Produced mainly in the Far East. Areca nuts are used mainly as masticatory. These nuts contain alkaloids (arecoline and arecaidine).
Around 55% of the weight in shell.
Around 25% of the weight in shell.
Around 55% of the weight in shell.
Around 53% of the weight in shell.
Around 50% of the weight in shell.

Scientific Name:
Including among all: 
Carya illinoensis 
Caryocar nuciferum 
Canarium spp. 
Lecythis zabucajo 
Macadamia ternifolia 
Pinus pinea
Common Name:
pecan nut 
butter or swarri nut 
pili nut, Java almond, Chinese olives 
paradise or sapucaia nut 
Queensland, macadamia nut 
pignolia nut
Definition: Other nuts that are not identified separately because of their minor relevance at the international level. Because of their limited local importance, some countries report nuts under this heading that are classified individually by FAO.
Mainly roasted, whether or not containing vegetable oils, salt, flavours, spices or other additives. Excludes prepared groundnuts, except when mixed with other nuts.
The most important oil crop. Also widely consumed as a bean and in the form of various derived products because of its high protein content, e.g. soya milk, meat, etc.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained by solvent extraction from the beans. Used mainly for food.
Oilcake and other solid residues (except dregs), whether or not ground, or in the form of pellets, resulting from the extraction of fats or oils.
A fermented soya product from defatted soybeans and wheat or other cereals that is filtered and pasteurized.
A fermented, salty condiment. Soya paste can be produced through brine fermentation of low- moisture soya curd.
Obtained by precipitating proteins from soya milk and removing the fluid. Can be fermented or non-fermented.
For trade data, groundnuts in shell are converted at 70% and reported on a shelled basis.
Used as direct food and for extracting oil.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained by pressure or solvent extraction. Used mainly for food.
Residue from oil extraction.
Roasted, salted, flavoured, etc
Obtained by grinding roasted peanuts. In addition to fat, at 40-46%, peanut butter contains all other components of the nuts.

In shell, covered by the endocarp, while exocarp (the smooth outer skin) and mesocarp (the fibrous covering) are removed. Immature nuts contain a milky juice that is consumed as a refreshing drink. Mature nuts are consumed as such, or processed for copra or desiccated coconut. The flesh, from which copra/oil is extracted, constitutes 40-70% of the weight of the husked coconut. The oil content is about 36% of the flesh.
Dried, shredded flesh of coconut processed for human consumption. It retains most of the oil and proteins of the fresh nut and is mainly used in confectionery and baking.
The dried flesh of coconut from which the oil is extracted.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained by pressure from copra and by solvent from the residues of pressure extraction. Has both food and industrial uses.
Residue from oil extraction.

The oil palm produces bunches containing a large number of fruits with the fleshy mesocarp enclosing a kernel that is covered by a very hard shell. FAO considers palm oil (coming from the pulp) and palm kernels to be primary products. The oil extraction rate from a bunch varies from 17 to 27% for palm oil, and from 4 to 10% for palm kernels.
Seeds of the oil palm. Babassu kernels (Orbignya speciosa) are often reported as palm kernels.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained from the mesocarp of the fruit of the oil palm by pressure, and also by solvent from the residues of the pressure extraction.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained from the kernel of the nut of the fruits of the oil palm by pressure in two or three stages at different temperatures. Including oil of babassu kernels.
Residue from oil extraction.
Includes table olives and olives for oil.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained from olives by mechanical or other physical means. Olive oil is the only vegetable oil that can be consumed without refining.
Treated with SO2, brine, water, or otherwise prepared or preserved.
Production data refer only to the nut contained in the fruit although the pulp around the nut is also edible.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: A very important vegetable oil in West Africa. Used as a substitute for cocoa butter and in cosmetics.
Valued mainly for their oil, which is used in pharmaceutical products. Ground seedcakes are used as fertilizers (castor oil pomace).

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained by pressure or by solvent. Uses include mainly industrial ones, in pharmaceuticals and cosmetics.
Valued mainly for its oil. Minor uses include as a human food and as feed for birds.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained by pressure extraction. Mainly for food use.
Residue from oil extraction. The cake is used for feed if it is from decorticated seeds, or for fertilizer if it comes from undecorticated seeds.
Valued mainly for its oil. Older varieties are rich in Erucic acid, which is considered unhealthy.

FCL Title: Oil of Rapeseed or Canola oil
Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained by pressure extraction for food use. Oil recovered with solvent from the residues of the pressure extraction is used for industrial purposes. Canola oil is produced from new varieties of rapeseed.
Residue from oil extraction.
Residues make up about 40% of the olives crushed for oil, but account for about 5% of the oil.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Oil extracted from olive residues with solvents.
Valued mainly for their oil.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained by pressure and used exclusively for industrial purposes. The resulting cake contains a toxic protein and thus cannot be used for feed.
From the shrub or small tree of the Buxaceae family.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained by cold pressure. Its peculiar chemical properties make it the only vegetable oil in nature having the same characteristics as spermaceti. Below 15ËC it solidifies and assumes the characteristics of wax. It is used as a lubricant, in cosmetics and in pharmaceuticals, and is considered a product with good growth prospects.
Valued mainly for its oil. Minor uses include as a human food and as poultry feed.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained either by pressure or by solvent. Has both food and industrial uses.
Residue from oil extraction.
Valued for its oil, but also as a food, either raw or roasted, as well as in bakery products and other food preparations.

Group: 14 - VEGETABLE AND ANIMAL OILS AND FATS
Definition: Obtained by pressure extraction in two or three stages at different temperatures. Sometimes the oil is also extracted by solvent from the residue of the pressure extraction. Used mainly for food.
Residue from oil extraction.

Scientific Name:
Brassica alba; Brassica hirta; Sinapis alba
Brassica nigra; Sinapis nigra
Definition: In addition to the oil extracted from them, white mustard seeds, may be processed into flour for food use. Black mustard seeds also yield oil and are processed into flour that is used mainly in pharmaceutical products.

Ploughs are implements designed to lift and turn soil. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.
Seeders are implements for sowing seeds or grain evenly in well-spaced rows at specific depths. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.

Manure spreaders and Fertiliser distributors are implements for spreading solid or liquid manure and distributing powder or granular fertilizers. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.
Combine harvesters - threshers are self-propelled machines that collect and thresh in one operation. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.

Balers (including pickup balers) are machines that collect grass, hay or straw after it has been cut. They form a round or square bale by compressing the material or tying it with twine wire, or a plastic wrap. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.
Root or tuber harvesting machines are implements used to harvest root and tubers. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.
Threshing machines (staking, forage harvesting) are machines that separate grain from straw. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.
Milking machines are used for milking cows, sheep, goats, etc. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.

Agricultural tractors, total generally refer to total wheel, crawler or track-laying type tractors and pedestrian tractors used in agriculture. Data are available for numbers in use in the agricultural sector as of 2000. Data on import and export in value and number are also available as of 1961.

Pedestrian controlled tractors are small tractors equipped with a single driving axle carried on one or two wheels. They are not usually fitted with a seat and the steering is effected by means of two handles. Some types, however, have a one- or two-wheeled rear carriage with a seat for the driver. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.

Agricultural tractors generally refer to wheel and crawler or track-laying type tractors (excluding garden tractors) used in agriculture. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.
Track-laying tractors are tractors which travel on steel or rubber or treads. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.

Other agricultural tractors include all other agricultural tractors that are not pedestrian controlled or track-lying, e.g. 4-wheel, 6-wheel, etc. Data are expressed in numbers in use in the agricultural sector.

Harvester and threshers refer to total harvesting and threshing machines as described by the Harmonised Coding System (HS) codes 8433 and 8437.10. Data refer to the value of the trade expressed in 1000 USD
Milking, dairy machinery refer to total milking and dairy machines as described by the Harmonised Coding System (HS) code 8434. Data refer to the value of the trade expressed in 1000 USD.
Soil machinery refers to total machines described by the Harmonised Coding System (HS) code 8432. Data refer to the value of the trade expressed in 1000 USD.

Agricultural machinery not else specified (n.e.s.) refer to total Agricultural machines as described by the Harmonised Coding System (HS) codes 8435-8436. Data refer to the value of the trade expressed in 1000 USD

Is a natural rock containing one or more calcium phosphate minerals of sufficient purity and quantity as to permit its use directly after grinding or after chemical processing in the manufacture of commercial phosphate fertilizers.
(NH3) is a material mostly produced by the synthetic process and at standard temperature and pressure is a gas. Fertilizer grade anhydrous ammonia contains about 82% of nitrogen.
KNONH3H2PO4 can be produced from naturally occurring sodium nitrate and potassium chloride and typically contains 13%N and 45% K2O.

CO(NH2)2, is produced from synthetic ammonia and carbon dioxide (CO2) and contains 46% nitrogen in ammoniac form. Urea may be in granular, prilled or crystalline form.
(NH4)2SO4, is produced by reacting ammonia with sulphuric acid (H2SO4). It is produced as fine white granules or crystals and contains not less than 20.6% nitrogen in ammoniac form.

(NH4NO3), is produced by neutralizing nitric acid (HNO3) with ammonia (NH3). Ammonium nitrate may be in white or off-white granular or prilled form and coated with a suitable material to prevent absorption of moisture and caking in storage. Pure ammonium nitrate may have a total nitrogen content of about 35%, of which one-half is present as ammoniac nitrogen and the other half as nitrate nitrogen.

NH4NO3+CaCO3, is produced from ammonium nitrate and finely pulverized calcium carbonate (CACO3). It contains not less than 20.5% and up to 28% of nitrogen, half of which is in the form of ammoniac nitrogen and the other half in the form of nitrate nitrogen. It is produced as white, off-white or grey granules or prills.

Superphosphate is a fertilizer produced by the action of concentrated sulfuric acid on powdered phosphate rock.
Is produced by the action of sulphuric and phosphoric acids on ground phosphate rock.
